ShingleMatrixFilter eaily throws StackOverFlow as the complexity of a matrix grows. ShingleMatrixFilter#next makes a recursive function invocation when the current permutation iterator is exhausted or if the current state of the permutation iterator already has produced an identical shingle. In a not too complex matrix this will require a gigabyte sized stack per thread.

My solution is to avoid the recursive invocation by refactoring like this:

{code:java}
public Token next(final Token reusableToken) throws IOException {
